    "id": "77473db5",
    "document": "Function: riscv_nn_maxpool_HWC_s8\nSummary: Replaced inner loop multiply-based addressing with precomputed pointer + stride addition\nApproach: Precomputed row_ptr base address before k_y loop and used col_ptr += in_tensor_ch for k_x advancement, eliminating the multiply (k_x + k_y * in_tensor_dim) * in_tensor_ch in the inner loop.\nCycles before: 25657\nCycles after: 25342\nSpeedup: 1.012x (1.2% improvement, essentially neutral)\nPipeline insight: Instruction count dropped 22.5% (10529 to 8164) but cycles barely changed (25657 to 25342). IPC dropped from 0.40 to 0.32. Function is clearly memory-bound by vector load latency at M8 e8 VLEN=1024 (128-byte loads).\nLesson: maxpool_HWC_s8 with in_tensor_ch=2048 and 3x3 kernel is memory-bound. Reducing scalar instruction count by 22% only saves 1.2% cycles. The bottleneck is VLSU throughput for 128-byte vle8 loads from strided addresses (stride=2048 bytes between k_x positions). Further optimization requires reducing total memory traffic, not instruction overhead.\nOutcome: neutral\nTags: maxpool, pointer-arithmetic, memory-bound, address-optimization",
