    "id": "fb9cda57",
    "document": "Function: riscv_nn_maxpool_HWC_s8\nSummary: M4 2-pixel parallel \u2014 neutral, memory-bound at M8 already\nApproach: Dropped LMUL from M8 to M4, processed 2 output pixels in parallel (separate accumulators v0/v4, separate load registers v8/v12). Goal: double memory-level parallelism. Result: IPC improved 0.32\u21920.57 but instruction count doubled (8192\u219214584). Net cycles: 25805 vs 25667 baseline (slight regression). The A/B pixel kernel loops are sequential so no true load interleaving occurs.\nCycles before: 25667\nCycles after: 25805\nSpeedup: 0.99x (neutral/slight regression)\nPipeline insight: vsim kernel extract at VLEN=512: M8 inner loop has 86-cycle period per vle8+vmax pair. vle8 VLSU latency is 27 cycles (issue\u2192VW8). vmax chains immediately after vle8 VW completes. With M8 the pipeline is fully serialized \u2014 only 1 vle8 and 1 vmax in flight at a time. Function is memory-bound on FPGA (ch=2048 >> L1 cache).\nLesson: maxpool_HWC_s8 is memory-bound \u2014 the hot loop is just vle8+vmax at M8 with no computation to hide behind. Reducing LMUL to M4 for 2-pixel parallelism doubles inst count without reducing cycles because the compiler emits sequential A/B loops (no interleaving). True improvement would require changing memory access patterns (e.g., blocking across output rows to reuse cache lines).\nOutcome: neutral\nTags: maxpool, memory-bound, LMUL, M8, M4, 2-pixel-parallel",
